<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>✨ RS003 Week 12 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> A Falling Starfield and Dropping Meteors · <strong>Course:</strong> Pygame Space Shooter · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week is about <strong>thinking about</strong> and <strong>explaining</strong> code that makes a background move. Stars fall down the screen, wrap back to the top when they leave the bottom, and meteors drift down at different speeds. Each star and meteor is a small <strong>dictionary</strong> of facts, and the program loops over a <strong>list</strong> of them every frame.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>🧠 Words to know: <strong>list</strong>, <strong>dictionary</strong>, <strong>fall</strong>, <strong>wrap-around</strong>, <strong>speed</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code and write what you think it does. You do not run anything — just think and write.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">stars = []
for i in range(80):
    stars.append({&quot;x&quot;: random.randint(0, WIDTH), &quot;y&quot;: random.randint(0, HEIGHT), &quot;speed&quot;: random.randint(1, 4)})
</code></pre>
<p><strong>This builds a list of 80 stars. What three facts does each star remember?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">star[&quot;y&quot;] = star[&quot;y&quot;] + star[&quot;speed&quot;]
if star[&quot;y&quot;] &gt; HEIGHT:
    star[&quot;y&quot;] = 0
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Each star moves down a little every frame. What happens when a star goes off the bottom edge?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">meteor[&quot;y&quot;] = meteor[&quot;y&quot;] + meteor[&quot;speed&quot;]
pygame.draw.circle(screen, (120, 120, 140), (meteor[&quot;x&quot;], int(meteor[&quot;y&quot;])), meteor[&quot;size&quot;])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Each meteor falls down at its own speed and each has a different <code>size</code>. What do the meteors look like together?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">meteors = []
for i in range(5):
    meteors.append({&quot;x&quot;: random.randint(0, WIDTH), &quot;y&quot;: random.randint(-200, 0), &quot;speed&quot;: random.uniform(1.0, 3.0), &quot;size&quot;: random.randint(15, 30)})
</code></pre>
<p><strong>This builds a list of 5 meteors. Why does each meteor start with a <code>y</code> value that can be a negative number?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block below was meant to do something but is broken. Write the fix, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — All the stars are supposed to fall at different speeds, but instead they all fall together in a solid wall.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">stars.append({&quot;x&quot;: random.randint(0, WIDTH), &quot;y&quot;: random.randint(0, HEIGHT), &quot;speed&quot;: 2})
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> every star has the same <code>speed</code>, so they all move the same.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — Stars should keep falling forever, but once they reach the bottom they never come back and the screen goes empty.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">star[&quot;y&quot;] = star[&quot;y&quot;] + star[&quot;speed&quot;]
pygame.draw.circle(screen, (255, 255, 255), (star[&quot;x&quot;], star[&quot;y&quot;]), 2)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> there is no wrap-around to send the star back to the top.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The program crashes when drawing a meteor because a position has a decimal point.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">meteor[&quot;y&quot;] = meteor[&quot;y&quot;] + meteor[&quot;speed&quot;]
pygame.draw.circle(screen, (120, 120, 140), (meteor[&quot;x&quot;], meteor[&quot;y&quot;]), meteor[&quot;size&quot;])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> <code>speed</code> is a decimal, so <code>meteor["y"]</code> becomes a decimal. Positions must be whole numbers.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Read this working example carefully. Then answer the questions below it. You are only reading — do not run it.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">import pygame
import random
pygame.init()

WIDTH, HEIGHT = 800, 600
screen = pygame.display.set_mode((WIDTH, HEIGHT))
clock = pygame.time.Clock()

stars = []
for i in range(80):
    stars.append({&quot;x&quot;: random.randint(0, WIDTH), &quot;y&quot;: random.randint(0, HEIGHT), &quot;speed&quot;: random.randint(1, 4)})

meteors = []
for i in range(5):
    meteors.append({&quot;x&quot;: random.randint(0, WIDTH), &quot;y&quot;: random.randint(-200, 0), &quot;speed&quot;: random.uniform(1.0, 3.0), &quot;size&quot;: random.randint(15, 30)})

running = True
while running:
    for event in pygame.event.get():
        if event.type == pygame.QUIT:
            running = False

    screen.fill((10, 12, 40))

    for star in stars:
        star[&quot;y&quot;] = star[&quot;y&quot;] + star[&quot;speed&quot;]
        if star[&quot;y&quot;] &gt; HEIGHT:
            star[&quot;y&quot;] = 0
            star[&quot;x&quot;] = random.randint(0, WIDTH)
        pygame.draw.circle(screen, (255, 255, 255), (star[&quot;x&quot;], star[&quot;y&quot;]), 2)

    for meteor in meteors:
        meteor[&quot;y&quot;] = meteor[&quot;y&quot;] + meteor[&quot;speed&quot;]
        if meteor[&quot;y&quot;] &gt; HEIGHT + meteor[&quot;size&quot;]:
            meteor[&quot;y&quot;] = -meteor[&quot;size&quot;]
            meteor[&quot;x&quot;] = random.randint(0, WIDTH)
        pygame.draw.circle(screen, (120, 120, 140), (meteor[&quot;x&quot;], int(meteor[&quot;y&quot;])), meteor[&quot;size&quot;])

    pygame.display.flip()
    clock.tick(60)

pygame.quit()
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What does the line <code>for star in stars:</code> do — what is it looping over?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>The line <code>star["y"] = star["y"] + star["speed"]</code> runs every frame. What does it make the star do?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Look at the wrap-around for the stars. How does the code send a star back to the top, and where does the star reappear?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does the meteor wrap-around use <code>&gt; HEIGHT + meteor["size"]</code> instead of just <code>&gt; HEIGHT</code>?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is <code>int(meteor["y"])</code> used when drawing the meteor but not when drawing the star?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Explain Your Lesson Code 🎥</h2>
<p>In today's live lesson you wrote your own moving background. Now make a short video on your phone explaining the code <strong>you</strong> wrote. You may show it running. Try to use these words: <strong>list</strong>, <strong>dictionary</strong>, <strong>fall</strong>, <strong>wrap-around</strong>, <strong>speed</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
